description: Ericson Silva has always had his biggest passion in music. He began experiencing various instruments since he was a kid, when he started his studies, becoming a multi-instrumentalist with classical graduation. In 1998, already experienced in music and aware of the demand for commercial tracks in the world of advertising, had his first contact with the electronic scene. That’s when Ericson discovers his true punch. From there to here, he combines formal knowledge and his main influences – original brazilian popular music and 90’s international music - to compose and produce with competence and strong personality. His productions always aim for the sample-free melodic originality, and can be classified in genres: eletrofunk, hip-hop, trip-hop, lounge, house, progressive-house and techno.

Davey Lawlor
Davey started as a full time musician in the local pubs at the early age of 19 in Brampton Ontario.
Recorded his first album 1996. He Sang backup for 3MDM at Massey Hall in 1996 opening for Runrig where he met Sam Reid (Keyboards Glass Tiger)Talked with Alan in our local pub (the Grey Goat), and said we should tour some of the Bars playing glass Tiger songs. Pub tour with Alan Frew started 1998/99
15 years ago. 
He then joined Alan Frew of Glass Tiger and toured his Solo Album ..Wonderland.. in 2000. 
In 2001 Davey toured through Germany preforming at the World Hockey Championships. 
In 2019 Davey was fortunate to be a co-writer on the new track Wae Yer Family that is featured on the new Glass Tiger 31 album.
Through the years Davey shared the stage with artists like Burton Cummings, Randy Bachman, 
The Tragically Hip, Blue Rodeo, and more. 

Davey currently resides in Ottawa ON and is focused on completing this new album.

The music that has aroused much enthusiasm in his young ears at the early age of eight was elaborated by the energy of the guitar sound. That has been the turning point, besides being the polestar of all his interests in life from than on. Writing his very first piece of music one year later, we surely are talking about a phenomenal musician. Soon afterwards he began to study the piano, but being persuaded by hearing his brother playing the drums, he decided to try it and, playing at sight, succeeded again. Having found the treasure trove instrument – the drums – he did not stop there. Founding a band, writing music and lyrics, performing and leading his playfellows was then his joy and passion. As all the dreams are finished one day, this has also… the band had split… But, having his head and ears, besides his golden hands, loaded with ideas, there had to be a solution. Stubborn as ever, J. Khobb had to compensate the black musical hole.Through some acquaintance, electronic music in general, the clubbing scene with all its attributes was introduced to him. Soon he realized that was all he ever wanted to do…to compose and produce with all his might… The main reason: independence in the process of creating jewels – musical masterpieces you really should discover!

Lukas Frei aka DubApe is a young and talented producer & DJ based in Austria. Originally specialized in deep, soulful beats around the 140bpm range, his 2012 debut release (as one half of the duo DubApes) on Bacon Dubs (“We Are Monkeys” EP) and its follow-up “Alteration” EP instantly reached the top of the online music retailer charts and won DubApe international recognition and support by Dubstep top dogs such as J:Kenzo, N-Type and Truth, just to mention a few.

In late 2015, with the release of “Meltdown” on Mainframe Recordings, his focus shifted mainly towards hard hitting Drum & Bass, after the duo parted ways. Last year saw this aspiring talent gaining attention amongst sophisticated followers of Drum & Bass music, by releasing heavy hitters like “Zero Point (feat. Deafblind”, “AI” or “Soundboy Killa”. Now, in 2017, the time has come for him to win over the big crowds – see infamous collabos with DisasZt (“Activate”/”Razor”) or the one with Phentix (“Get it” and “Silk Road”). DubApe´s productions stand out, melding dark, atmospheric sounds with ethnic textures define an instantly recognizable sound and style.

On the DJ front – DubApe has already performed all over Austria and played shows in Berlin, Bratislava and the UK – more shows are planned for 2017.

Memory Splice is an Electronic Music Production/DJ and Music Production Software duo.  First signed to Christopher Lawrence's label Pharmacy Music and featured by electronic music icon Paul Van Dyk, their debut EP, ”Vermillion/Antropy” spent 28 straight days on the Beatport Top 100 Trance Release chart, peaking at #16,  they've since had 3 successful releases and their record for excellence continues on the Spanish based TFB Records.

 Memory Splice is based around husband and wife team Pixie and Sonny Bruner. They use intense sound design and big sound palettes, layers upon layers, mind-warping automation and effects to only further showcase their talent for strong melodic uplifting or aggressive tech-heavy electronic music, music that blurs and transcends genres and subgenre. 

Memory Splice is always pushing ahead embracing modernism, these artists work in harmony to bring together and burn the bridges of classic and progressive trance and house using controllerism and all that technology can offer and will offer, to create and recreate a time-bubble of when listening to Electronic Music and going to underground parties and clubs was an immersive, communal, and intense listening and dancing experience. 

They are supported by noted dance music DJ/Producers including M.I.K.E. Push, Guiseppe Ottaviani, Manuel LaSaux, Sean Tyas, Talla 2XLC, Paul Oakenfold, Thomas Datt, Paul Trainer, Kaeno, Allen & Envy, Liquid Soul, PVD, French Skies, Karybde & Scylla, and many more. Memory Splice are monthly residents at EU based Soundtraffic.pl!

We love making new friends (and Pixie only bites if asked nicely!)

I am a composer of classical and electro-acoustic music.  My interests encompass theological meaning in music and the use of non-traditional forms of music in worship.  While I do take very seriously the spiritual side of my compositions, I also write/create music for the sake of self-expression.
  
  I am always open to artistic collaboration, so if you like what you hear and would like to collaborate on a project, please let me know.  Also, if you would like a higher quality recording of any of these recordings, please feel free to contact me.  Thank you for your support.

Clothing designer who became DJ or DJ who started designing clothes? Who knows? 

Herr Beckman is the designer of the famous fashion brand These Glory Days, but you probably have gathered, is his love for music as great as his love for clothes. 

You might think that Herr Beckman has designed clothes all his life, think again ... 

As a 14-year-old began his DJ career in the small town of Nora in Sweden, after 5 years of constant playing Eurodisco, everyone could understands that a break was inevitable. 7 years later, he has promised to give the profession another chance, now as a free man, he can finally express himself as an eclectic DJ. 

With a crazy mix of house, synth, electro, 70s, 80s, cosmisc disco, a plethora of remixes & one other known hitpick, is a perfectly ordinary evening of Herr Beckman. 
There is no genre or artist that are prohibited to play, either to find, but an innovative remix or cut the song himself into something better than the original. Most of the songs you probably have not heard all too many times, unknown remixes, new classics found from a past so long as it is as solid and dance-friendly, it is permissible.

Technology is a keyword in the development of electronic music in the world and also influences the artistic evolution of João Komka. Born and raised in the heart of Brazil, Brasília, he started his career in the early 00s and always kept close to the transformations that were taking place in the scene.

He saw Electroclash coming and was hooked by the identity of this sound, creating a visceral fixation for synthesizers. Besides bet on his work as DJ and producer, Komka dedicated a great part of his life as co-founder and artistic director of 5uinto, label party responsible for putting Brasília on the route of major international tours and bringing more than 450 artists to the city. Today, disconnected from the brand, he puts his artistic career first and brings many experiences and achievements through his almost 20 years of career. As a DJ, there were dozens of gigs of the renowned D-EDGE, a constant presence at Universo Paralello, toured in Asia, performing in four cities of China and two of Indonesia, many memories throughout Brazil.

His work as a producer has already been praised by Laurent Garnier, DJ Hell, Boys Noize, and through Come and Hell, his old project with Mariana Perrelli, he released "Take Control" alongside Gui Boratto on Kompakt, also produced "Heavy Rain" with Xenia Beliayeva. In 2019, he founded his record label, I/U Music. He started 2020 with an EP on D.O.C Records, "Disconnected Rails".

Now, his true artistic essence will be printed on his first album, "Untenable System", which completely reveals all his facets, bringing dark atmospheres, analog sounds, acid and broken, carrying a message that reflects the collapse of the unfair and unsustainable current system. It is an authentic work, full of personality, with an experimental and eclectic approach that escapes the most obvious paths and proves his musical maturity.

I like harsh noise, pretty noise, music that sounds broken, ambient experiments, acoustic guitar, distortion, improvised music, lo-fi sounds, and long walks on the beach. 

This is a place for some of my random experiments and strange ideas. It's all the result of spontaneous and mostly ghetto hardware experimentation.

Afrolicious Bio -

Afrolicious, the live/electronic collective based in the San Francisco Bay Area started out not as a band but as a club night at the famed Elbo Room in The Mission District in 2007.  The format of Afrolicious party was very open and included the DJs spinning the latest soulful dance music including Afro-House, broken beat, modern funk and disco alongside classics and re-edits and remixes of their favorite Afrobeat, Salsa, and Brazilian funk alongside live percussionists and guest MCs and musicians. Eventually morphing into a live band led by the production and arrangement skills of Pleasuremaker, many dancers, DJs and producers began to take notice of their unique sound.  

Since the release of their first two EPs which were produced by Rob Garza of Thievery Corporation, the reputation of the band and founding DJs Pleasuremaker and Señor Oz have grown and they have performed everywhere from Red Rocks, Burning Man, Cielo and the Greek Theatre in Berkeley. "We never planned on becoming a live band, but like everything else about Afrolicious it happened organically," says Oz. "When we started the party, it was truly what we thought the Mission was about. It wasn't exclusive and it wasn't exclusionary, it was open to everyone. The youngest person in our collective is the rising soul singer Ziek McCarter who started with us at 19. Our oldest member is Baba Duru, who moved to SF in 1970 and toured with Stevie Wonder. Our vocalist is from Trinidad and our drummer is from Brazil. We all congregated in SF over our love of the universal groove. There are rhythms that connect all dance music from the beginning of time to the present day and we believed we could transmit them."  

In 2013 they released their debut full-length album, California Dreaming on their own label, Afrolicious Music. IN 2014 they assembled some of the finest DJs and producers from around the world to remix their debut album. California Dreaming Remixed features remixes from Jamaican dub legend Scientist, Rob Garza from Thievery Corporation, Peruvian electronic live hybrid Novalima, Brazilian nu-disco producer Trotter, Australia’s Omegaman, Miami’s Stereo 77 and the Bay Area’s DJ Smash, J Boogie, Izzy Wise and Antonio Guedes.



  Afrolicious is also loosely affiliated with a worldwide group of DJs, producers, bands, and labels who produce contemporary soulful dance music inspired by sounds of the African diaspora, including Antibalas, Chico Mann, Nickodemus, DJ Smash, Wonderwheel Recordings, Subsuelo, and Cumba Mela.

The creative director, DJ & producer has a flair for reading and connecting with the crowd, creating that mercilessly upbeat and unpredictable sound that makes us feel emotion on the dance floor.

Simply put, Salah Sadeq’s music is the joy in a child's eyes when he does something naughty and knows he'll get away with it.

A passionate global artist who, for the last 24 years, has thrived in the field of music and design, he has developed his sound across time, collaborating with a number of high profile international and regional artists, venues, labels, agencies and brands.

An experience of Salah’s magical sets is one that remains with you for days, weeks and months. It’s from within his passionate soul that he reaches out, with a style of music that spans deep - house - groovy - electronica - techno - acid - disco - dub - abstract beats and pieces that get under your skin; a truly experienced versatile style that never fails to infect the listener with a dirty groove.

Born and raised in Bahrain, he developed his skills from the very young age of 14, performing at the infamous “Tameem” night club, varied underground gigs, which led to him becoming the weekend resident DJ at “Likwid” Bahrain from 1999. Gradually, he took over running his own nights at the club, on the island, and in the region, building a reputation that resonated with his Dutch audience in Amsterdam, where he began to make his mark on the international circuit.

Close to home, he has played alongside a number of big artists in Dubai, too many to list, with Laurent Garnier, Josh Wink, and Sven Väth being stand-out moments for Salah.

His adventures have seen him play in Berlin, Amsterdam, Toronto, and Tbilisi. He’s been behind the decks across Europe and the Middle East, and toured India.
Aside from repeat returns to Amsterdam Dance Event, he’s played at Pacha Festival Amsterdam, Silver Network Anniversary @ Showcase Paris, and Sven Väth’s 2015 Tour in Beirut, as well as at a few intimate gigs at the iconic Studio 80 Amsterdam, The Woods Brussels, and Lisi Woods Tbilisi.

Collaborations are some of his favourite things, working and sharing across artistic endeavours, and he’s been a part of projects with Beirut In The Mix, Half Baked in Dubai, Ohm Event’s Ill Communications, Electric Days, Infusion Magazine. He’s built the popular weekly radio show The Crate. His concept Techfui, born out of his early days in Bahrain, is the definitive ethos of his artistic and creative self, and has invited guest DJs like Ame (Frank Wiedemann), Peace Division, Mazi, and more. The Techfui ethos has lived on with his sets, collaborations and the family has grown, with the label launching in 2014.

On a brief hiatus in his homeland Bahrain after living between Dubai and Tbilisi, Salah is a regular at leading venues and nights in the scene. His love for mixing music has, in recent years, lead to regular productions and collaborations, seeing Salah release his first EP aptly titled “Techfui” on Gold Drama Recordings featuring Jef K, Salar Ansari, Hoolz, and Mi.Key in 2014. Shortly afterwards, he released his second EP “Paris with a K” on One28 Recordings with remixes from Jef K and Ronin & Nesta. Since then, he’s worked on a number of collaborations, 2016 seeing the release of EP “4 Blondes” on Stripped Off with Kay aka Khalil Touihri, “Ummm” on Enfant and 2017 starting off with “Sleep Smoker” on Proper Slap with Hoolz. 

His latest collaboration effort has seen him team up with Cheh as duo “Saché & Saché” with a V.A. EP out on Ukrainian label Nastroy, a couple of remixes under his Salacious alias for his brother Sadeq on Diametral and Rada on QM Allstars. Known for not sitting around Salah has kept himself busy during the said hiatus with new collars with Rashed Aldhaen seeing light in 2019.

Meditation on music,
Machine enlightenment,
Zen Tek!

Although people imply an aweful lot of seriousness when talking about the idea of zen (and techno for that matter...),
I am not some uber-minimal head-nodding jaded master. Zen/music *is* serious stuff, with tremendous power, but some people take it too seriously!

Imagine a 3 year old who reads too many fantasy books and has a drum machine and a passion for psychedelic experience. . And you might be halfway to understanding where I'm coming from! hahah.

Honestly actually, my driving goal, is to perfect the art of music-hypnotism (AKA "trance" / "entrancing") with a view to take people on journeys, and quite possibly implant rebellious anti-society messages in their minds while they are under my spell. I think music to me is the closest thing I have seen to magic that exists outside of my own mind. Magic is cool. Not like "Haha I made your watch disappear" magic. . but like. . shoot lightning from hands, etc etc.

Some people say music is a drug, but I think chemicals, music, art, performances. . they are magic. Forces that control our perception of time, space, our thoughts, our feelings, our desires.

Oh and just to scare you all, when I was in primary school I used to want to take over the world. . now commencing phase 1 of Operation Birdcage!

So to sum up my major spiel (now do you see how I am torn between something like buddhism and the righteous life, and.. my childish desires to just play and imagine?)

I am a very escapist person, who wants to create fantasy around me and within my own mind. I plan on doing this by performing LIVE music, so that I can create a kind of rift in time space, where my imagination controls myself and everyone around me for just a little while. I'd like to get into throwing themed parties that tie in with the journey I want to deliver as well. That would be excellent.

Sometimes I stop trying to escape and consider changing the physical world/human society and the way I (and others) act in it. This shows through as radical anti-society sentiment. I'm usually too lazy to act on it though.

I want to make music that has deep psychological impact, but that is still approachable and fun.

So far the technical name for this style stands as something like this:
Psy-prog-tech-break-trance-dub

I hope you've enjoyed reading my enormous profile,
I haven't actually made any music for this project yet, so I'm off to do that now. BRB!

PS: Also the name is supposed to reflect some of the philosophical thoughts I have about consciousness, artificial intelligence, the issue of transhuman/cyborg/robot rights/humanness/'self' persistency, etc.. The mind boggles, but boggling is kinda fun.

Garry Mkrtchyan (aka Fabien Kamb)


Born in Yerevan, Armenia - Garry Mkrtchyan is the man acting as DJ, musician and producer under the stage name Fabien Kamb. Making his first musical steps back in the 90's, while being totally blown away with the ever-growing electronic sounds, Garry made his initial attemps in starting a career as a producer as he started to research sound production and engineering. Since then, he has established himself to produce electronic music covering a wide range of genres like Ambient / IDM / Drum'n'Bass, while simultaneously experimenting with various sounds. During this period of time, Garry collaborated with many like-minded people, eventually finding a production colleague and true friend in Ashot Babayan (also known as Krummstoff), with whom he founded the duo "Mad and Spectral". Creating numerous tunes based on organic house rhythms while deeply flavored with jazz, funk and soul music, the duo introduced a solid track record in collaboration with many vocal performers and session musicians. Moving forward MaS launched another project by the name of Salt Sweet which was mostly oriented at creating progressive house tracks and later on evoked two separate aliases: Fabien Kamb (for Garry Mkrtchyan) and Krummstoff (for Ashot Babyan). Fabien Kamb's angle concerning the ever-evolving house music trends and his sense of self confidence places him among the internationally renowned DJs and producers of our time.

Surely enough, the list of record labels wishing to have Fabien on board, and the number of other artists wishing to have him remix one of their tracks is constantly growing.

The music of Fabien Kamb is a pure reflection of the whole spectrum of his musical researches and sound engineering experiments, which at this point are mostly concentrated at tech- and deep house and are reflected in his album which was released on Plastic City end of september 2011 in cooperation with Low Flow Records from Armenia. His everlasting curiosity and his ability to melt the vibes of the clubs into his tracks have made way for his album "Origin" and it's 11 ecstatic tunes that cut right to the chase - both from the angle of musicality and sound engineering.

Music Style: Jazzy House/Housey Jazz. I’ve been collecting records since I was about 12 and was inspired by the likes of Mastermind, Rapattack, Les Adams and Froggy, who all mixed in such a way that just blew me away and got me hooked on underground dance music. I started mixing by using a tape deck and a belt drive turntable and learnt to mix and scratch my tunes like that, by pushing the tape and phono buttons in at the same time. This is something I do not recommend, as I had to get my Dad’s amp repaired far too many times. I got to try out my newfound skills at the tender young of 13, when I was at one of my elder sister’s friend’s party and the Dj had to go home and get another crate of records. He said to me, “It’s all yours, shouldn’t be too long….” After playing for a about three hours, I realised I could do the things my idols did and the things I did at home very easily with two turntables and I could also make people dance. I’d got the bug! Since then I have played at many events world wide watching the scene change, being part of the original house explosion in the UK, playing at the groundbreaking raves like Sunrise, Energy and Biology to name but a few. The music I play now is heavily influenced by jazz, something that I put down to the music I was fed by my parents as a young child, the likes of Grover Washington, Stanley Turentine, Dizzy, James Brown, Quincy Jones, Duke Ellington, Count Basie and also soca, reggae, hi life, funk and soul and disco, an eclectic mix of black music to whet any young boys appetite for music. I currently present “A Nu Breed Of Jazz” on PushFm each and every Thursday 20.00 - 22.00 GMT and am resident at the House Of Rhythm and play at various parties in and around London. Am also currently reworking many of the tunes I have produced over the years and starting new ones.

It is fitting that composer and pianist Fabrizio Paterlini was born and lives in the ancient northern Italian city of Mantua. A romantic and historically significant centre of musical and artistic excellence, the city’s elegance and cultural depth permeate Paterlini’s exquisite original solo piano compositions. Yet despite Mantua’s unavoidable influence in informing the composer’s work, his cinematic music is far from localized, or even recognizably Italian, instead tapping directly into universal human emotions.

Listeners and critics alike are torn as to how best label Paterlini’s beautiful sound. Neo-classical, Ambient, Minimalist and New Age have all been considered, but it is more pertinent to note some of the adjectives regularly used in appreciation of his sonic palette. Ethereal, soulful, lush, emotive, dreamy, delicate and, tellingly, passionate, all appear with unerring frequency. The composer himself describes his work as “like a glass of red wine on a summer evening,” in awareness of the calming effect of his reflective melodies on the listener.

Paterlini began playing piano at six-years-old. From the first moment he stroked the keys his life irrevocably changed, music becoming “a choice made every day...explored in all its aspects.” And so music and his life’s path became, and remain, inextricably linked; while he progresses as a musician and composer, so his development as a human being runs parallel. Formal study in his chosen artistic endeavour came with five years at Campiani’s Academy, Mantua’s Academy of Arts, from where he graduated in Music Theory.

The 1990s saw Paterlini extensively cutting his teeth as a gigging musician by performing rock classics, pop and jazz in local bands. While playing with these outfits he began to compose music, at this stage principally material of a progressive rock persuasion. As the decade and century drew to a close Paterlini reached an important decision, being to concentrate exclusively on the piano – the instrument that, in his own words, “best expresses his inner world.” Yet it was not until 2006 that he began composing music for solo piano.

In the following year his life’s musical journey took a momentous step with the release of his debut CD, Viaggi in Aeromobile (Travel in Aircraft) on the Music Center label. A collection of beautifully structured, graceful mood pieces displaying Paterlini’s natural touch and seemingly effortless talents, the release was warmly received in Italian specialist press. 

2008 saw the issue of an EP previewing Paterlini’s sophomore full-length, Viandanze, which was to follow on his new Fabrizio Paterlini Records imprint in December, 2009. In the interim the 8-track Remixed collection, offered as a free download on his website, presented the composer’s material as subtly reworked soundscapes, comfortably easing them into cogent chillout territory. Viandanze was partially funded by donations from Paterlini’s burgeoning fanbase, and performed in 2010 at Teatro Verdi in Mantua.

Prestige festival appearances then preceded the 2010 release of the flawless Fragments Found CD, again on Paterlini’s own label, drawing comparisons with luminaries such as Ludovico Einaudi, Erik Satie and George Winston.

2011 saw the issue of the double CD set “Fragments Found + Viandanze”, published under the Japanese label Inpairtment/P*DIS. 
During the Fall of the same year, he started working to his “Autumn Stories” project, by composing, recording and releasing on-line one song for each week of the Autumn season. The project resulted in the CD “Autumn Stories”, published in February 2012. 
 
The increasing number of fans sharing his music on the net, led him to “Piano_Anders #3” Festival in Hasselt (BE) in the month of February 2013. Two months later, he released his new full album “Now”, followed by an exclusive release in Japan (P*DIS). This release, acclaimed by specialized magazines as Headphone Commute (US) and A Closer Listen (UK), will bring him to tour Russia in the month of November 2013 and Japan in the month of January 2014.

Koris is an artist of trajectory. Trajectory of sets, which the DJ and producer of Swiss origin knows how to put together like sensitive trips, on the outer borders of contemporary electronic trends. An artist’s trajectory too, as Koris is coming back front stage after exploring other creative fields – contemporary dance, urban happening and event layouts.

Coming back to music as well as returning to being himself. A major figure of the international scene since the early 2000s, he is now letting personal inclinations blossom more than ever in terms of deep house, techno and IDM. The eclecticism of his selections envelops the body as much as the mind: in the connections which link one track to another, emerges an organic space, an invitation to poetry and escape.

Starting point: an adolescence of synthesizers, turntables and samplers, tucked away in the basement of the family home, Koris tried out his ear and technique. He was soon invited to the biggest festivals: Mayday, Energy, Street Parade. A set in San Francisco in front of thousands of people in a disused warehouse, launched a career spanning Europe, the United States, Russia and Japan.

With a commitment to making the pulse serve emotion, Koris favors human dimensions of music, powered at the heart of machines as much as in terms of the imagination.

At a time when a new generation of labels and listeners is allowing a culture, which has long been confined to the night, be brought into the light, Koris wants to defend a techno which is one of sharing. "Today, styles and audiences are combining in new ways. I want to go towards this spontaneity."

An innovative, flexible techno is the trajectory which is already shining its first golden light of tomorrow.

LDBK (pronounced Laid Back) was first established in 2002 in Brussels as a FM radio show

Sten-Kristian Saluveer / Sten Gun is Estonian born and Japan based electronic music and film producer whose work ranges from club music to film scoring, sound and multimedia design as well as cinematic productions.
Trained as classical guitarist, over his some 20 year ranging career he has released music under various monikers such as Tranceman, Sten Gun, Adrian Allstars, Coincidence and Umblu to name a few as well as produced and mixed records, as well as served as producer, DJ and keyboardist more than 20 years for diverse range of artists:
from house legend Cassioware, NYC Ibadan mastermind Jerome Sydenham,
 Grammy-Award winning drummer Brian Melvin to Estonian jazz singer Sofia Rubina, indie rock legend Röövel Ööbik and many others!
Additionally he has worked with classical artists, including ETV’s Girl Choir performing original compositions at Metropolitan Opera, Riverside Church, Hilton Ballroom and other classical venues. Most recently, the collaboration saw commissioning of electronic remixes for world acclaimed choral composer, Veljo Tormis’ epic “ The Making of Sampo” by Estonian National Broadcasting.

“The Wild Hunt blog is a must-read for those interested in news and events dealing with the modern Pagan and Heathen communities – and religion coverage in general.” – M.Z. Hemingway, Get Religion

“…a source for smart commentary on a broad range of news, media, and ideas from a pagan perspective.” – Jeff Sharlet, author of “The Family: The Secret Fundamentalism at the Heart of American Power”.

The Wild Hunt is primary destination for those interested in following news relating and of interest to modern Pagan religions and other minority faiths. Founded by Jason Pitzl-Waters in 2004, The Wild Hunt has grown to become one of the most-visited and popular destinations exploring these topics. Recruited to Patheos.com in the Summer of 2011, The Wild Hunt decided to exist as an independent entity once more in the Summer of 2012. In addition, The Wild Hunt has now expanded into a media outlet with paid contributors and two paid staff members.
